<sect1 id="XMLDECODE">
  <!-- DNT-Start --><title>XMLDECODE</title><!-- DNT-End -->

  <para><emphasis role="bold"><!-- DNT-Start -->XMLDECODE<!-- DNT-End --><indexterm>
      <primary><!-- DNT-Start -->XMLDECODE<!-- DNT-End --></primary>
    </indexterm><indexterm>
      <primary><!-- DNT-Start -->XMLDECODE<!-- DNT-End --> Function</primary>
    </indexterm>(</emphasis><emphasis> unicode </emphasis><emphasis
  role="bold">)</emphasis></para>

  <para><informaltable colsep="1" frame="all" rowsep="1">
      <tgroup cols="2">
        <colspec colwidth="77.05pt" />

        <colspec colwidth="275.75pt" />

        <tbody>
          <row>
            <entry><!-- DNT-Start --><emphasis>unicode</emphasis><!-- DNT-End --></entry>

            <entry>The unicode text to decode.</entry>
          </row>

          <row>
            <entry><!-- DNT-Start -->Return:<!-- DNT-End --></entry>

            <entry><!-- DNT-Start -->XMLDECODE<!-- DNT-End --> returns a single value.</entry>
          </row>
        </tbody>
      </tgroup>
    </informaltable></para>

  <para>The <emphasis role="bold"><!-- DNT-Start -->XMLDECODE<!-- DNT-End --></emphasis> function decodes
  special characters into an <!-- DNT-Start -->XML<!-- DNT-End --> string (for example, &amp;lt is converted to
  &lt;) allowing you to use the <!-- DNT-Start -->CSV<!-- DNT-End --> option on <!-- DNT-Start -->OUTPUT<!-- DNT-End --> to produce more complex
  <!-- DNT-Start -->XML<!-- DNT-End --> files than are possible by using the <!-- DNT-Start -->XML<!-- DNT-End --> option.</para>

  <para>Example:</para>

  <!-- DNT-Start --><programlisting>  d := XMLENCODE('&lt;xml version 1&gt;&lt;tag&gt;data&lt;/tag&gt;');
  e := XMLDECODE(d);</programlisting><!-- DNT-End -->

  <para>See Also: <link linkend="XMLENCODE"><!-- DNT-Start -->XMLENCODE<!-- DNT-End --></link></para>
</sect1>
